We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Direct all officials concerned to immediately refund/settle in full their outstanding cash advances; 
Resort to the withholding of salaries of accountable officers and employees if still unable or persistently refuse to settle/liquidate their cash advances; 
File appropriate charges under existing laws against the erring officials or employees; and
Henceforth, strictly monitor and ensure that no additional cash advance is granted to accountable officers with unsettled balances.

We recommended that the LCE:
Direct the concerned offices to hasten the implementation of the partially and unimplemented PPAs under 20 per cent DF to fully attain the desired socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes essential to the promotion of the general welfare of its constituents;
Adopt a well-defined strategy to enhance the present monitoring and review activities during the planning, procurement, contract implementation and program evaluation phase, in order for the planners and implementers to continuously monitor the timely implementation, so that immediate appropriate and corrective actions could be done on noted gaps along the way;
Make an assessment of all PPAs not yet implemented to determine whether the funding for such PPAs are necessary, if not then revert to the unappropriated surplus and reprogram to development projects of utmost concern of the Municipality;
Provide appropriation on the debt servicing paid without corresponding appropriation amounting to ₱374,206.72, if feasible sourced from savings of implemented completed PPAs in CY  2021 and from others sources; and
Evaluate PPAs on financial assistance to Civil Society Organization (CSO) an appropriation under 20 per cent DF not align with development programs and considered as ineligible for funding under 20 per cent DF for realignment to cover the deficit in appropriation in debt servicing.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

For monitoring and disclosure, require the information system admin to enhance the aging module of the accounting system to reflect fairly the age of accounts;
Impose strict compliance with the rules and regulations on the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;
Require all officials concerned to immediately refund/settle in full their outstanding cash advances; and

Enforce Section 128 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445 or erring personnel.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to make final verification, reconciliation and accounting of these Due to LGUs account balances;

In case of amounts received or collected for the account of other LGUs and shares in the income of other LGUs, timely account and remit the same;

In case of balances of various transfers from other LGU intended for certain Projects, Programs and Activities (PPAs) which have already been long completed, prepare the Disbursement Vouchers (DVs) together with the supporting schedule for the Municipal Treasurer to issue a check payable to the source agencies/LGUs. Those funds which are considered as special purpose funds shall be retained and those balances for which original releases is in the nature of financial assistance or subsidy and for which the agreement do not mention of the disposition of the unused balance, these maybe reverted to the unappropriated surplus and future utilization thereof subject to the usual accounting, auditing and budgeting laws and regulations; and 
Ensure that recording of amounts in the Subsidiary Ledger (SL), at the minimum, should clearly describes the name of the specific LGU from which the amounts were received/collected/held and the specific description of the PPAs to which the funds relate. Likewise, documents relating to these amounts should be kept properly for verification and reconciliation purposes, as the need arises.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to make the final verification, reconciliation and accounting of these account balances;

In case of recently received funds which remained unutilized as of year-end, ensure its timely utilization based on the respective PPA’s implementation schedule;

In case of long been completed PPAs, prepare the DVs together with the supporting schedule for the Municipal Treasurer to issue a check payable either to the source agency or direct to the National Treasury. Those funds which are considered as special purpose funds shall be retained and those balances for which original releases are in the nature of financial assistance or subsidy and for which the agreement do not mention of the disposition of the unused balance, these maybe reverted to the unappropriated surplus of the Municipality, for future utilization thereof, subject to the usual accounting, auditing and budgeting laws and regulations; and
Ensure that recording of amounts in the SL, at the minimum, should clearly describes the name of the specific source agency from which the funds were received and the specific description of the PPAs to which the funds were intended. Likewise, release documents relating to these funds should be kept properly for verification and reconciliation purposes, as the need arises.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Direct the BAC to require the concerned contractors to renew the performance or warranty security, as the case may be, in accordance to the prescribed period for these securities in the R-IRR of RA No. 9184, and furnish the Auditor a copy thereof;
Require the BAC and Municipal Engineering Office (MEO) to designate personnel to monitor the implementation of infrastructure projects particularly ensuring that the contractors are informed and required to post performance and warranty securities timely and appropriately;
Ensure to make the issuance of Certificate of Final Acceptance after the defects liability period as a matter of policy by the LGU for the determination of the propriety of the period of coverage of the warranty security posted by the contractor and which shall also signify of the timely release of the retention money to the contractor;
Evaluate which performance and warranty securities are still actually binding and effective but does not bear a date of coverage or with erroneous date of coverage in its face and require the insurance company concerned to supplementing it or correct it, as the case may be;
Evaluate the completeness of the essential entries (such as, but not limited to, the period covered by the policy) required in performance and warranty securities posted in favor of the LGU before its acceptance to ensure its enforceability; and
Ensure compliance the provisions of 2016 R-IRR of RA No. 9184 as to the performance and warranty securities.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to review all the transactions/Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) before encoding the data in the system;
Ensure that the system is updated with day to day transaction to facilitate the timely submission of the FS;
Review and apply the necessary corrections and adjustments for any errors or deficiencies before finalizing the FS; and
Strictly follow the provisions of Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standard (PPSAS) especially the presentation of FS and the qualitative characteristics of the information it provides.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Direct the Bid and Bid and Awards Committee (BAC) to require the concerned contractors to renew the performance or warranty security, as the case may be, in accordance to the prescribed period for these securities in the R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184, and furnish the Auditor a copy thereof;
Require the BAC and MEO to designate a personnel to monitor the implementation of infrastructure projects particularly ensuring that the contractors are informed and required to post performance and warranty securities timely and appropriately;
